# Introduction #

This notebook explores patterns in the Top 500 Novels dataset and its relationship to New York Times bestseller data using exploratory data analysis (EDA). The goal is to identify trends in genre distribution, publication history, ratings, and pronoun usage, and to consider potential biases in literary representation.

# Load Data #
import pandas as pd
import altair as alt

# Load datasets #
novels_df = pd.read_csv(
    "https://raw.githubusercontent.com/melaniewalsh/responsible-datasets-in-context/main/datasets/top-500-novels/final_merged_dataset_no_full_text.tsv",
    sep="\t"
)

nyt_df = pd.read_csv(
    "https://raw.githubusercontent.com/ecds/post45-datasets/main/nyt_full.tsv",
    sep="\t"
)
# Data Cleaning #
nyt_df = nyt_df.rename(columns={'title': 'nyt_title'})
nyt_df['title'] = nyt_df['nyt_title'].str.title()

# Merge datasets #
combined_df = novels_df.merge(
    nyt_df,
    how='left',
    on=['author', 'title']
)
# Initial Exploration #
combined_df.info()
combined_df.describe()
combined_df.isna().sum()
combined_df.head()

The dataset contains 500 novels with metadata such as genre, publication year, and ratings. Some columns contain missing values, particularly in author-related metadata.

# Visualization 1: Number of Novels by Genre #
alt.Chart(combined_df).mark_bar().encode(
    x='genre:N',
    y='count():Q'
).properties(
    title='Number of Novels by Genre'
)

This graph shows how novels are distributed across genres. Some genres appear much more frequently, suggesting possible bias in how the “top 500” novels were selected.

# Visualization 2: Publication Trends Over Time #
combined_df['pub_date'] = pd.to_datetime(
    combined_df['pub_year'].astype(str) + '-01-01'
)

alt.Chart(combined_df).mark_bar().encode(
    x='pub_date:T',
    y='count():Q',
    color='genre:N'
).properties(
    title='Publication Trends Over Time'
)

This visualization shows how different genres are distributed across time. It suggests that certain genres became more popular in later periods.

# Visualization 3: Average Goodreads Rating by Genre #
alt.Chart(combined_df).mark_bar().encode(
    x='genre:N',
    y='mean(gr_avg_rating):Q'
).properties(
    title='Average Goodreads Rating by Genre'
)

This graph compares average ratings across genres, showing whether some genres tend to receive higher reader ratings.

# Visualization 4: Pronoun Usage by Genre #
melted_df = pd.melt(
    combined_df,
    id_vars=['genre'],
    value_vars=['he_counts', 'she_counts', 'they_counts'],
    var_name='pronoun',
    value_name='count'
)

alt.Chart(melted_df).mark_bar().encode(
    x='genre:N',
    y='sum(count):Q',
    color='pronoun:N'
).properties(
    title='Pronoun Usage by Genre'
)

This visualization shows how pronouns are used across genres. Masculine pronouns often appear more frequently, which may reflect gender bias in literary texts.
